05097nam a22007095i 9781526155283DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a2023553533  a97815261552837 a10.7765/97815261552832doi  a(DE-B1597)660614  a(OCoLC)1382698015  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB00aG156.5.W66bG54 2022. 4aG156.5.W66bG54 2022 7aHIS0150502bisacsh04a306.48192231 aGleadhill, Emma, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTaking travel home :bThe souvenir culture of British women tourists, 1750–1830 /cEmma Gleadhill. 1aManchester : bManchester University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b15 colour illustrations, 32 black & white illustrations, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGender in History00tFront Matter -- tDedication -- tContents -- tPlates and figures -- tAcknowledgements -- tMap of the central women travellers’ residences in England, Wales and Ireland -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Gendering connoisseurship -- t1 The Grand Tour -- t2 Shopping for souvenirs -- t3 Creating their own cultural capital -- tPart II: Gendering science -- t4 Every fair Columbus -- t5 Dorothy Richardson’s extensive knowledge -- t6 Lady Elizabeth Holland, the social orchestrator of science -- tPart III: Gendering friendship -- t7 From diplomatic gift to trifle from Tunbridge Wells -- t8 A snuff-box and other Napoleonic keepsakes -- t9 Princess Ekaterina Dashkova’s gifts to Martha Wilmot -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tPlates0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the late eighteenth-century, elite British women had an unprecedented opportunity to travel. Taking travel home uncovers the souvenir culture these women developed around the texts and objects they brought back with them to realise their ambitions in the arenas of connoisseurship, friendship and science.Key characters include forty-three-year-old Hester Piozzi (Thrale), who honeymooned in Italy; thirty-one-year-old Anna Miller, who accompanied her husband on a Grand Tour; Dorothy Richardson, who undertook various tours of England from the ages of twelve to fifty-two; and the sisters Katherine and Martha Wilmot, who travelled to Russia in their late twenties. The supreme tourist of the book, the political salon hostess Lady Elizabeth Holland, travelled to many countries with her husband, including Paris, where she met Napoleon, and Spain during the Peninsular War.Using a methodology informed by literary and design theory, art history, material culture studies and tourism studies, the book examines a wide range of objects, from painted fans “of the ruins of Rome for a sequin apiece” and the Pope’s “bless’d beads”, to lava from Vesuvius and pieces of Stonehenge. It argues that the rise of the souvenir is representative of female agency, as women used their souvenirs to form spaces in which they could create and control their own travel narratives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSouvenirs (Keepsakes)zGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aTravelxHistoryy18th century. 0aWomen touristszGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Georgian Era (1714-1837).2bisacsh  aElizabeth Vassall Fox Holland.  aEnlightenment.  aGrand Tour.  aHester Lynch Thrale Piozzi.  acuriosity cabinet.  aeighteenth century.  agender history.  amaterial culture.  asouvenir.  athing theory.1 aGleadhill, Emma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University P